          title: 'Mode of Exercising Legislative Power: Money Bills',
          content:
            '(1) The provisions of this section shall apply to:\n(a) an appropriation bill or a supplementary appropriation bill, including any other bill for the payment, issue or withdrawal from the Consolidated Revenue Fund or any other public fund of the Federation of any money charged thereon or any alteration in the amount of such a payment, issue or withdrawal; and\n(b) a bill for the imposition of or increase in any tax, duty or fee or any reduction, withdrawal or cancellation thereof.\n(2) Where a bill to which this section applies is passed by one of the Houses of the National Assembly but is not passed by the other House within a period of two months from the commencement of a financial year, the President of the Senate shall within fourteen days thereafter arrange for and convene a meeting of the joint finance committee to examine the bill and agree on an appropriate version.\n(3) Where the joint finance committee fails to agree within the specified period, the bill shall be presented to the National Assembly sitting at a joint meeting, and if the bill is passed at such joint meeting, it shall be presented to the President for assent.\n(4) Where the President fails to signify his assent to a money bill within thirty days, it shall be deemed to have been assented to.',
          plainEnglish:
            'Money bills (budget, taxes, spending) have special rules. If one chamber passes a money bill but the other does not within 2 months of the financial year, a joint committee meets to work out differences. If the committee fails, both chambers meet jointly to vote. If the President does not sign a money bill within 30 days, it automatically becomes law.',
          relatedCases: [],
          tags: ['money bills', 'budget', 'appropriation', 'taxes', 'legislature'],
          lastAmended: null,
